

This is the current state of the patch.  Bootstrapped and regtested it on x86, 
power10, and aarch64.

Thanks.

-


This patch adds backpropagation of demand-bit information to the
backprop pass.  It is intended to catch cases like this

  int
  foo (int in)
    {
      int a = in & 0xff;
      int b = a << 1;
      int c = b & 0xf;
      return c;
    }

  int a = x & 0xFF;
  int b = a << 1;
  int c = b & 0xF;
  int d = a + y;
  return c + (d & 0x7);

where we can propagate B's demand of 0xf back to IN and elide the
& 0xff masking.

The implementation is rather simple for now, handling
BIT_AND_EXPR, MULT_EXPR, LSHIFT_EXPR, RSHIFT_EXPR, and
PLUS_EXPR, MINUS_EXPR.

Once the demand has reached a BIT_AND_EXPR and we see that it does not
exceed what we mask off anyway, we elide the mask.

	PR tree-optimization/113487
	PR tree-optimization/122209

